Goal of the thread: Make a shopping list of things that you need, consider if there is any self care things you might be missing!
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

Typically when it comes to changing habits it involves replacing them with newer habits. You should find new hobbies and thoughts that excite and interest you to replace the old. Make a list of these things and find new activities or thoughts to replace it with.
That all said, remember that forced change in personality isn't natural change. If these are things you like and bring you joy, forcing yourself not to enjoy them will only make you miserable. >>29421448
Something that has helped me in the past is to eat more, smaller meals throughout the day. I don't try to fight the urges to snack, but instead plan around those urges. As long as you count the calories to ensure you are hitting your goal intake, how frequently you eat isn't a problem. For example, one of my go-to snacks/meals is a couple tablespoons (~50 cals) of hummus, some carrot sticks (~30 cals), and maybe a piece of flatbread (~100-150 cals). Other favorite snacks include a handful of nuts (peanuts, almonds, cashews, etc) or fruits (especially apples and bananas). Drinking plenty of water is also key, as always, and your friend may find that green or black tea helps (caffeine is a moderate appetite suppressant) .

>1. Do you know of any mysteries?
Yes. One "mystery" that I'm very interested in is the Finders cult.
A mysterious child trafficking new age cult that was found transporting children across the US-Mexico border. It had ties to a Satanic panic case that the FBI had found actual evidence of being real, including secret tunnels with pentagram iconography.
The FBI continued investigating and searching Finders cult related properties. They had found cages on a farmhouse that seemed to have been used to keep children locked away.
The FBI continued working with border patrol and local police agencies and felt as though they were close to finding out the truth. They had flight logs, purchasing history, etc. and it all seemed to be pointing to an international child trafficking ring that involved incredibly rich individuals who had properties in a number of countries including all the way out in China.
All of a sudden the CIA came into the case, declared it an internal matter while sucking up all of the evidence.
Shortly thereafter the case was declared "closed" and the CIA never continued looking into the Finders cult.
No one knows why they did what they did, where the evidence went ,etc.
All we have are semi-declassified FBI documents. They were only declassified a few years ago and prior to that you could actually find those same documents floating around online.
Of course, back then everyone thought they had to be fake. Because I mean, the FBI investigating a new-age satanic child trafficking cult and the CIA stepping in sounds insane, right?
Well, one day they declassify the matter and it turns out those images were real leaked images of these same documents.
And no one, absolutely no one, knows what happened to the Finders cult.
There were never any charges in spite of the evidence, no one knows what happened to the driver that had kids in the truck, etc.

Tell me about prior experiences where this happened and go into detail (where did you meet this person, what were their reactions that made you feel like they were purposely avoiding you, what do you think caused this, what did you talk about for the period before they started ignoring you, etc)
For non autistic people generally the more practice you get talking to people, the easier it gets and the more you pick up on small social cues. For instance I used to overshare wayyy too much and then realized that it's done in levels (talk about stuff thats extremely mundane, then stuff that's slightly emotional but still super not controversial, then slightly more personal/controversial, etc) because going too fast freaks people out.
A lot of stuff I didn't pick up on though and other people also had to explicitly tell me. Like me being needy. Now I spread out my neediness so no one feels overburdened by it.
No idea how this changes if you're autistic but you can still try. And although there are fewer people who are very comfortable with weirdness, there will definitely be SOME people who are okay with your weirdness, you just need to find them. Actively telling people you're autistic may also help? If I tell people I have PTSD then they're way way more forgiving of weird quirks I have.
Don't just give up though. And if something doesn't work out for some reason and you can't figure out why, try to talk to that person about why they're distant now so you have more information and if it's not something major then you can apologize and say that you'll try to work on it (though imo it's kinda a red flag sometimes when someone just drops you without talking to you about it, but other times it's definitely your fault because they drop hints but you just don't pick up on them)

>>29423934
It'll probably get easier over time. And people in general don't notice others unless those others make themselves noticed, so if you're quiet then it makes sense that not that many people approach you.
I used to have really beautiful long hair, and I kid you not, I'd get complimented on it almost every day. Now I look like the most generic guy in the world so I have to do the majority of the effort in reaching out to strangers. So if you wanted others to approach you without doing much, you could drastically change your appearance to be something "cool" that people comment on.
Otherwise you're gonna have to speak up a bit. But some parts of that are difficult because you don't really know when other people are done speaking and it's easy to accidentally interrupt other people. *Especially* when talking to a bunch of extroverts. (And desu, sometimes it's not that people are quiet, it's that loud people don't shut up enough or invite quiet people to talk enough or give them space to talk etc).
Quieter social groups are generally easier to navigate that in. I've never been to them, but I feel like book clubs and knitting/crochet groups and other similar stuff are probably quieter. Otherwise, you'll have to be a bit more forward.
You could explain what your autism means if it seems like some people don't get it. But hey, people communicating with you and asking you why you're a certain way is a good thing, it opens the floor to explain yourself and just say that's the way you are, and verbalize your actual opinions/feelings, that you felt good there. Use your words.
There's also always the option to just talk to other autistic people.

>>29416013
>why does nobody ever explain how this works lol
Because for most people, an intellectual understanding of how it works won't get you any closer to being able to actually do it.

Voice training is trying to teach you how to raise your larynx and how to shape your mouth cavity, first of all to shrink the resonant space in your vocal tract because that's the #1 contributor to perceived genderedness of voices, but also to try and teach you to shape your mouth cavity in a way that selectively amplifies certain frequency ranges (upper mid-range) and dampens others (super high and mid to low range). The problem is that most people cannot consciously control the muscles that do this, nor can they consciously learn to do it by rote. Instead, the most effective approach is to create exercises that the conscious brain can focus on that basically trick your body into learning how to unconsciously control the right muscles and give you the muscle memory to be able to consistently do it on command. Because of how this works, you're better off trying different exercises and practising them all until you find the one(s) that work for you rather than spending your time intellectualizing them.

Big dog little dog, whisper siren, sliding from oooooo to eeeeeeee, and cat hissing are all just different tricks to try and teach your body to unconsciously do the same thing. Try them all, rotate between them, eventually your body should learn what it needs to. Once it learns to raise the larynx, then you can focus on learning to minimize mouth resonance.

>>29426995
Ok, I'll try and explain how voice training works in a really simple way. Basically, the goal is to shrink the space in your throat and your mouth (in the right way where it doesn't cause strain) so that your voice has a much smaller space to resonate in, which causes it to sound 'smaller'. Making your voice sound smaller is the #1 most important goal of voice training, and it means you have to learn to raise the larynx in your throat, and to shape your mouth and tongue in such a way as to make the space inside your mouth smaller and so that it amplifies upper mid-range frequencies but dampens low range and super high frequencies.

The hard part is that most people cannot consciously identify and control the right muscles so you can't learn to do this by being told which muscles to use and learn it by rote practice. Instead, exercises try to teach you indirectly by giving you something to mentally focus on and mimic that can help you learn to unconsciously control the right muscles.

This is what all the popular exercises like big dog little dog, whisper siren, hissing cat, oooo to eeeee slides, and so on are trying to do. But since they're all indirect mental tricks, different ones work better for different people, and you should try a bunch to see which works best for you.

Once you have those two aspects of voice training down, then you can work on speaking a bit softer and on raising pitch, if necessary (but not too much!).

To use a weird analogy, it's like Buddhism. Buddhists often say that different schools/approaches to Buddhism are all different fingers pointing at the same moon, and trying to find a "best" school is mistaking the finger for the moon. A point in the novels is that Tanya's brain is very broken and disordered. Thinking about it in hindsight makes so much sense on why I finally felt like I found a character to relate to - it's because Tanya literally thinks 24/7 everyone around her wants her dead. On top of them experiencing weird gender bender shit it was literally the perfect character for a traumatized tran like me.

I think the constant survival mindset has some uses, as I genuinely think experiencing life solely through that lens has taught me some very important lessons, but I would also say it's not really something anyone should ever aspire for.

Yes, I was hyper vigilant every single day of my life, yes I was extremely quick on my feet, yes I could read people extremely well, yes I wasn't worried about any of the bullshit, but the brain isn't supposed to work in survival mode constantly. After just a few hours of it, your brain gets exhausted - I only had energy immediately after waking up or if I was able to keep myself distracted in my room. A lot of people called me high, because of my general low spatial awareness (plus complete disregard for unuseful social conventions), which manifested after utter exhaustion from the vigilance.

About 2 years ago I had a moment where I was 0.4 seconds from being ran over by a train which was going full speed. I was too exhausted to pay attention (forced outside). After I realized what happened, I just shrugged it off and kept going on with my day - only in hindsight did I realize how odd of a response that is. I'm always in survive or die mode, so coming close to death didn't change my state from normal to hyper focused about to die, because I was always in the latter state already.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
I still have trauma issues but I have an absolute shitload of trauma from several decades of child abuse, rape, beatings, etc (and now mom suicide). However, I am light years better now than I was back when I was a little teen on 4chan, and I've recovered a LOT compared to my lowest periods.

EMDR helped me when I was reeling from domestic violence, couldn't cope with lying down in bed at night or trying to sleep, having flashbacks all day and nightmares all night. I'm revisiting it again and slowly getting myself out of where I was from my mom dying, and I'm noticing that even though this has been one of the darkest periods of my life, right BEFORE she died, I was actually emotionally healthier than I've ever been, and I'm recovering faster than I ever have from trauma. I'm rapidly getting back a lot of the skills and good self-esteem I had from years of being separated from my family of origin.

Things that helped me:
>EMDR, as I said (more for the actual trauma)
>DBT, including using the workbooks or free online study groups for it (more for coping with emotional breakdowns, attachment/relationship problems and distress in the moment). regulating your behavior will take an additional stress off you
>getting the fuck away from whoeverr might have contributed to the CPTSD.
>art
>support groups like Adult Survivors of Child Abuse, or recovery groups for addiction problems
>anxiety + flashback meds like beta blockers, used carefully
>making sure I am eating ok, SLEEPING OK, and hydrated.
>meditation (which I don't recommend for everyone bc it can worsen mental health problems. for me, though, it's been great. I have to do it every day to get enough practice in
>looking up what an emotional flashback is so iI know how to deescalate them
>comfort/safety items
>animals

sorry fo any typos. very very tired

I don't think I'm communicating properly. The Greeks we are speaking of had none of these modern concepts of gender fluidity. Rather, they had very common and rigid ideas of gender and adored them differently. It was because of these articulated and idolized forms and legends that oddities among men and myth had any reason to be uniquely interesting. They recognized distinct genders enough to have a binary premise, which has a lot of implications: polarity, duality, opposites. They also continue this with 'man' and 'animal'.

This in no way resembles modern gender theory. In modern gender theory, biology is innately blurred and there is supposed to be nothing surprising about men in dresses in public spaces fully believing they are simultaneously sane and women, and moreover complaining that not enough people are playing along at every level. In modern gender theory, sexual fluidity is the default normal. In Hellenist Greece, it is an escape from established polarity and exceptional in myth and intimacy.
